---
/*
 * S07ToolsVsHooks.astro — Tools vs Hooks section
 *
 * Two-zone layout (iyo-clean pattern):
 *   Entry:  Eyebrow "TOOLS VS HOOKS" (azure) + BlurReveal headline + lead
 *   Body:   Two GlassCard comparison blocks — AI decides vs code decides
 *           "The code quality problem" — same task, two approaches
 *           "Hook priority cascade" — 5 priority levels
 *
 * background="slate"   mode="technical" (azure eyebrow)
 * Content sourced from: .design/sections/07-tools-vs-hooks.md
 */
import Section from '../components/sections/Section.astro';
import Eyebrow from '../components/content/Eyebrow.astro';
import BlurReveal from '../components/content/BlurReveal.astro';
import GlassCard from '../components/content/GlassCard.astro';
import NumberedRow from '../components/content/NumberedRow.astro';
import UpNextTeaser from '../components/content/UpNextTeaser.astro';
---

<Section id="s7" label="Tools vs Hooks" background="slate">
  <Fragment slot="entry">
    <Eyebrow label="TOOLS VS HOOKS" mode="technical" />
    <BlurReveal>
      <h2>Tools are capabilities the AI controls. Hooks control the AI without it knowing.</h2>
    </BlurReveal>
    <p class="lead">
      Both are modules. Both plug in the same way. But they operate in fundamentally different
      realms, and using the wrong one for a task produces unreliable behavior.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <!-- ── Comparison blocks ────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="comparison">

    <GlassCard>
      <h3>Tools — 'The AI decides'</h3>
      <p>
        Available tools are listed in the AI's system prompt. The model sees each tool's
        name, description, and input schema. When the model decides it needs to take an
        action, it generates a tool call. The model looks at the user's request, considers
        its available tools, and chooses intentionally. Tool calls appear in the conversation
        history. The result appears in the conversation history. Everything is visible,
        traceable, and explainable. Reading files, writing files, searching the web, running
        commands. Tools extend what the model can do.
      </p>
    </GlassCard>

    <GlassCard>
      <h3>Hooks — 'Code decides'</h3>
      <p>
        Hook Handlers respond to events in the system. When something happens, an event
        fires. Hook Handlers that have registered for that event run automatically. The AI
        model has no idea that hooks exist. Hooks do not appear in the model's instructions.
        They are not listed in the system prompt. The model cannot see them, cannot call
        them, cannot choose to use them. Hooks operate entirely in the system layer. Getting
        user permission, safety-checking operations, monitoring context and injecting
        relevant information, logging events. Hooks govern what the model is allowed to do.
      </p>
    </GlassCard>

  </div>

  <!-- ── The code quality problem ─────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="subsection">
    <h3>The code quality problem</h3>
    <p>
      You want every file the AI writes to pass a code quality check. Two approaches:
    </p>
    <p>
      As a tool: You give the AI a run_code_checker tool and tell it in its instructions to
      always run it after writing a file. The problem? The AI might forget. It might decide
      the check isn't needed this time. It might get sidetracked by the user's follow-up
      question. You're relying on the model's compliance with an instruction, which is
      probabilistic, not guaranteed.
    </p>
    <p>
      As a hook: You register a Hook Handler for the tool:post event, which fires after any
      tool completes. When the event fires for a file-writing tool, the hook runs the code
      checker. If it finds issues, it injects a message: 'The code checker found 3 issues on
      lines 12, 15, and 22.' The AI reads this on its next turn and fixes the issues. The
      check happens every single time, regardless of what the model decides.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Hook priority cascade ────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="subsection">
    <h3>Hook priority cascade</h3>
    <div class="cascade">
      <NumberedRow
        number="—"
        label="Deny (highest)"
        description="Highest priority. One deny blocks the entire operation. No further hooks execute. Fail-closed security posture."
      />
      <NumberedRow
        number="—"
        label="AskUser"
        description="Pauses execution for a human decision. First one wins."
      />
      <NumberedRow
        number="—"
        label="InjectContext"
        description="Multiple hooks accumulate. All messages are merged and added to conversation history."
      />
      <NumberedRow
        number="—"
        label="Modify"
        description="Transforms data flowing through the event. Multiple modify hooks chain."
      />
      <NumberedRow
        number="—"
        label="Continue (lowest)"
        description="The default. No-op. The event passes through unmodified."
      />
    </div>
  </div>

  <img
    src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}diagrams/tools-vs-hooks.svg`}
    alt="Tools are LLM-decided, Hooks are code-decided"
    class="diagram"
  />

  <UpNextTeaser
    nextSection="Sessions"
    teaser="A session is a container."
  />
</Section>

<style>
  /* ── Entry zone ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  h2 {
    max-width: 20ch;
  }

  .lead {
    font-size: clamp(1.125rem, 1.2vw, 1.25rem);
    line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
    color: var(--text-body);
    max-width: 55ch;
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
  }

  /* ── Comparison blocks ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

  .comparison {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    max-width: 60ch;
  }

  .comparison :global(h3) {
    font-size: var(--text-body);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--text-primary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .comparison :global(p) {
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
    color: var(--text-body);
    margin-top: var(--space-2);
  }

  /* ── Sub-sections (code quality problem + cascade) ────────────────────────── */

  .subsection {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    max-width: 60ch;
    color: var(--text-body);
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
  }

  .subsection h3 {
    font-size: var(--text-body);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--text-primary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-1);
  }

  .subsection p {
    line-height: var(--leading-normal);
  }

  .cascade {
    margin-top: var(--space-2);
  }

  /* ── Diagram ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .diagram {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: var(--space-8) 0;
    opacity: 0.9;
  }
</style>
